The java.lang.string.join() method concatenates the given elements with the delimiter and returns the concatenated string.
Note that if an element is null, then null is added.

String.join(" < ", "Four", "Five", "Six", "Seven");
Four < Five < Six < Seven


String.join("  ", "My", "name", "is", "Niraj", "Pandey");
My name is Niraj Pandey


String.join("-> ", "Wake up", "Eat", "Play", "Sleep", "Wake up");
Wake up-> Eat-> Play-> Sleep-> Wake up



String []word1 = {"abc", "d", "defg"};
System.out.println(String.join("", word1));
abcddefg
